commit_message:
Port API types extra specs to Python 3

* Replace dict.iteritems() with dict.items(). The iteritems() method
  of dictionaries was removed in Python 3.
* Add cinder.tests.unit.api.contrib tests to tests-py3.txt:

  - test_availability_zones
  - test_capabilities
  - test_extended_snapshot_attributes
  - test_hosts
  - test_qos_specs_manage
  - test_quotas
  - test_quotas_classes
  - test_scheduler_stats
  - test_services
  - test_types_extra_specs
  - test_types_manage
  - test_used_limits

Partial-Implements: blueprint cinder-python3
Change-Id: Ie3d2de456c34286cca0505f6125a1a723bd8ad8b

Add -f option to formatting volumes to xfs

If volume is not empty we can have a bug
in formatting to xfs
Closes-bug: #1506857

commit_message:
Explicitly specify 'puppet_modules' for tasks

In Astute, we have a strict validation that 'puppet_modules' must
present in puppet task declaration; otherwise fail deployment. That
means 'puppet_modules' is not allowed to be an empty string.

This validation is presented only for pre/post deployment tasks, and
isn't performed for deployment tasks. But let's be pessimistic, and
force users to specify 'puppet_modules' explicitly even if it's
current working directory.

Change-Id: I63e546545077bea15f62c8ac8682c682895e5935
Closes-Bug: #1506624

commit_message:
Merge of two backported commits for fixing liberty gate

Use LOG.error when no exception handler is used

There's no need to use LOG.exception here since sys.exc_info()
results in (None, None, None) and thus would effectively just
be LOG.error.

Also, the failure of invoking LOG.exception outside of an
exception handler is due to a bug in Python3[1]. The fix for
that is only available in Python3.5.

[1] http://bugs.python.org/issue17911

Closes-Bug: #1482261

Change-Id: I9ceac0fceafa45769cc15f56027c981182ff0750
(cherry picked from commit f5c415accfff2ad399194b30b9408a903042f009)

Add testresources used by oslo.db fixture

If we use oslo.db fixtures, we'll need these 2 packages or
the next version of oslo.db release will break us.

Change-Id: I71f001c8b75ad52e68ccab8f07cd8946772fd03b
Closes-Bug: #1503501
(cherry picked from commit a7368fb68e8c1cccbb601aa1aad444248c645c25)

commit_message:
update swift_hadoop element

This change replaces the hardcoded value for the hadoop swift jar
filename with a variable that defaults to the old value
"hadoop-swift.jar" but also allows redefinition.

* add variables for hadoop swift jar file name
* add documentation for new variable
* correct documentation for the lib path variable
* add more to the basic description documentation

Change-Id: I44eaaa8b23ae30231b7b4087740d8dd5d050ec00
Closes-Bug: 1498967

commit_message:
generatepot-rst: dedicate logic to generate common-rst.pot

Previously common-rst.pot is additive only and
deleted strings in the source document will remain forever.
This commit make generatepot-rst.sh not reuse existing
common-rst.pot and generate the POT file from scratch.

This patch creates an index rst file which includes all
files under common-rst and generate common-rst.pot.
By doing so, all contents of common-rst can be covered.

Closes-Bug: #1507138
Change-Id: I888f37ad5e14a0e1cc7d182e376acaf63f98e565

commit_message:
Check grace_period before use it

CLUSTER_SCALE_IN action can be attached by deletion policy and
scaling policy, but action data is different.
Deletion policy's action data:
{"deletion":
     { "candidates": [],
       "grace_period": 20,
       "destroy_before_deletion": False}
}
Scaling policy's action data:
{"deletion": {"count": 2}}

Change-Id: I2dd9dbec2fbfb08eb6c41e4552d91ed84550ab49

commit_message:
Update paths due to stackforge migration.

fuel-library repository has been moved from stackforge/ to openstack/ namespace.

fuel-tasklib repository got deprecated during migration, but it appears it is
still used in fuel-library CI. We add temporary workaround to run CI job
using fuel-tasklib package from fixed commit. The problem will be properly resolved
via related bug #1507208.

Change-Id: I8e2342c869a27fa1bb104fd46138ad27270f2d73
Related-Bug: #1507208

commit_message:
Move openstackdocsstheme to blacklist

The project openstackdocstheme does not need to be constrained, the
projects always use the latest version. Dsvm jobs or regular unit tests
do not use it for now.

Move package to the blacklist.

Change-Id: Idbb596a94b15e0006afc2de05af8259f236074b6
(cherry picked from commit 3905e916cad28b840d19facfd0f61bc3bb099d71)

Move openstackdocsstheme to blacklist

The project openstackdocstheme does not need to be constrained, the
projects always use the latest version. Dsvm jobs or regular unit tests

[{'created': '2015-08-05 21:38:38.000000000', 'message': 'Fixed glance.tests.unit.test_artifacts_plugin_loader unit-test

The test code gets full path of module when _setup_loader() calls.
Getting full path of mudule could occur test failure
in indivisual environment.
Made the test glance.tests.unit.test_artifacts_plugin_loader
independent of working directory of current user.
Closes-Bug: #1439951
Change-Id: I05015cc84aeb48770177c9e26e91cd49aa327657
(cherry picked from commit 2fbe06c36c0bd645499f2324796f9617fd3056ac)
'}]
commit_message:
Fixed glance.tests.unit.test_artifacts_plugin_loader unit-test

The test code gets full path of module when _setup_loader() calls.
Getting full path of mudule could occur test failure
in indivisual environment.
Made the test glance.tests.unit.test_artifacts_plugin_loader
independent of working directory of current user.
Closes-Bug: #1439951
Change-Id: I05015cc84aeb48770177c9e26e91cd49aa327657
(cherry picked from commit 2fbe06c36c0bd645499f2324796f9617fd3056ac)

commit_message:
per-project -core and -release groups for Fuel

As agreed on openstack-dev [0], we need separate core reviewers groups
for Fuel repositories. This commit adds fuel-specs-core group, restricts
release actions from core groups to the fuel-release group, and replaces
refs/heads/stable/* pattern with explicit mention of stable/7.0 branch
for fuel-mirror.

That last bit is necessary since we have a time gap between creating a
stable branch (at soft code freeze [1]) and handing the responsibility
for it to the fuel-stable-core team (at release). Because of this, we
can't limit merge permissions to all stable branches to the stable team,
during soft code freeze all core reviewers should remain able to merge
backported commits to the new stable branch.

[0] http://lists.openstack.org/pipermail/openstack-dev/2015-September/075093.html
[1] http://lists.openstack.org/pipermail/openstack-dev/2015-August/073110.html

Change-Id: I850cae66c660b2c35ec4c5e2c45ad57c61108af3

commit_message:
Avoid python34 tests for oslo.vmware in kilo and juno

In stable/{juno,kilo} oslo.vmware requires suds, suds is not python3
compatible.

Do not run the python34 job for oslo.vmware on stable/{juno,kilo}
branches

Change-Id: I803001180a17da7c2bb725c38201fba721684a04

commit_message:
Add fast format option in the Storwize Driver section

Add option for user to disable fast format at thick
provisioned volume creation in IBM Storwize cinder.
The default value is False and clients who do not want
to do Fast Format for thick volume, they can set this
parameter to True.

Change-Id: I85d36e0b67615c56fd87bcc2759b910935e4d97d
Closes-Bug: 1504412

commit_message:
Bump upper constraints of oslo.config to 2.5.0

Gnocchi is trying to use the new ListOpt option interface released in
oslo.config version 2.5.0, so we need to bump the upper constraints to
avoid jenkins failure.

Change-Id: Iebfff9de606c1e9cb995751a00b86b10ba26f61b

This review should be based on https://review.openstack.org/#/c/218059/ which normalizes the way users and projects are named.  Otherwise, the logic for doing fetch_user and fetch_project will need to be the way it is done now, which is much more complicated (that is, you can't assume a name by itself means name::Default)."}, {'account_id': 6525, 'date': '2015-09-23 23:30:04.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 5:

> This review should be based on https://review.openstack.org/#/c/218059/ which normalizes the way users and projects are named.

The purpose of that review is to add deprecation message when ::domain (composite title without title_patterns) is not used. This is not a normalization of anything and it cannot pretend fixing the inconsistent use of the domain parameter (like in the user case where the tenant can be passed without a domain).
Therefore the indirection fix doesn't not need to depend on.
(Read on)

> Otherwise the logic for doing fetch_user and fetch_project will need to be the way it is done now, which is much more complicated (that is, you can't assume a name by itself means name::Default).

Yes it can, because the existing code is flawed we have to patch and more fixes to come along.
The best example is the user case (mentioned above), where I just added tenant_domain property to the user provider."}, {'account_id': 8297, 'date': '2015-09-24 10:30:56.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5: Code-Review-1

(2 comments)

Nice refactoring of the tests.  For the jenkins error I think you have to modify the test manifest to add your tenant_domain parameter to the user creation.'}, {'account_id': 9983, 'date': '2015-09-24 16:07:44.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 5: Code-Review-1

To sum up what was discussed on IRC yesterday:

This patch doesn't work with the current code.  With the current code, you can say::

    keystone_tenant {'project': domain => 'somedomain'}
    keystone_user_role { 'someuser@project': ...}

and the keystone_user_role code will know that 'project' is 'project' in the domain 'somedomain', even though 'somedomain' is not the default domain, because the keystone_tenant.self.instances code will look for 'project' in all domains and will use it without '::somedomain' if there is only one project named 'project' in all domains.

We have decided that this logic is unnecessarily complex, and instead have decided that 'project' should mean 'project::Default', and 'project::somedomain' should always be qualified with the '::domain'.  This is implemented in https://review.openstack.org/#/c/218059/

However, 218059 is really implementing two different things:
1) warning if the user tries to specify 'project' without a '::domain' if not in the default domain
2) changing the logic of self.instances to do the 'project' should mean 'project::Default', and 'project::somedomain' should always be qualified with the '::domain'

Therefore it was proposed that 218059 be split to implement 1) and 2) separately.  Then, this review 226624 should be rebased on 2), and 1) should be postponed until we know the results of Sofer's investigation of multi-component puppet resource naming."}, {'account_id': 9983, 'date': '2015-09-24 16:16:11.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 5:

Not exactly.

I think the order should be this:

Review 218059 should be first.  Any supporting code that 218059 needs from 218044 should be removed from 218044 and added to 218059.  That is, 218044 should only contain the code that does the '::domain' checking and deprecation warnings.

Then, 226624 should be rebased on top of the new 218059.  Then, depending on what Sofer finds, we should do 218044 last."}, {'account_id': 6525, 'date': '2015-09-25 13:05:07.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5:

This patch is going to be made dependent upon review [1] instead to make it less cumbersome.

tl;dr - Yes, this patch deliberately breaks backwards compatibility, in a way that was discussed on the openstack-dev list and in the puppet openstack meetings.  To wit: A domain scoped resource _must_ be qualified with the 'resource_name::resource_domain_name' if _not_ in the 'Default' domain.  The recommended fix to puppet-heat is below.

The problem is here::

    ensure_resource('keystone_user_role',  ${domain_admin}@::${domain_name}", {
      'roles' => ['admin'],
    })

Based on the hiera values and the class default parameters, this means "assign the user 'heat_admin' in the unspecified domain to have the domain scoped role 'admin' in the 'heat_stack' domain".  It is a domain scoped role, not a project scoped role, because in "@::heat_stack" there is no project, only a domain.  Note that the domain for the 'heat_admin' user is unspecified.  In order to specify the domain you must use 'heat_admin::heat_stack@::heat_stack'.  This is the recommended fix - to fully qualify the user + domain.

This patch does break backwards compatibility.  In the old code, there was some complicated (and neither-able-nor-willing-to-be-supported) code that would search all of the domains to find the unique user named 'heat_admin'.  The implementation was changed to say "if a user is specified without a domain qualifier, it must be in the Default domain.  If you want to refer to a user that is not in the Default domain, you must qualify it with ::domain".  From the logs::

    2015-10-02 06:07:39.574 | Debug: Executing '/usr/bin/openstack user show --format shell heat_admin --domain Default'
    2015-10-02 06:07:40.505 | Error: /Stage[main]/Heat::Keystone::Domain/Keystone_user_role[heat_admin@::heat]: Could not evaluate: No user heat_admin with domain  found

This is from the keystone_user_role code.  Since the role user was specified as 'heat_admin' instead of 'heat_admin::heat_stack', the keystone_user_role code looks for 'heat_admin' in the 'Default' domain and can't find it, and raises an error.'}, {'account_id': 3153, 'date': '2015-10-07 18:15:21.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 15:

This patch is going to "break" all modules using service_identity. I would like to see patches in others modules that Depends-On this patch and reflect the needed change to update the way we use keystone_user, etc.

Otherwise, I think the patch is good and we can move forward. My opinion says it's okay to break backward compatibility early, while we have a few domain/v3 users at this time.'}, {'account_id': 3153, 'date': '2015-10-07 23:12:23.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 15: Code-Review+2

commit_message:
Replace indirection calls

Indirection calls are replaced with #fetch_project and #fetch_user methods
using python-openstackclient (OSC).

Also removes the assumption that if a resource is unique within a domain space
then the domain doesn't have to be specified.

Closes-Bug: #1493450
Change-Id: I36fabf547fa50fc14d49f491f11cb4a0571f7d31

Do not run constraints jobs on old stable branches

We should not attempt to run these jobs on Juno or Kilo.

commit_message:
Split test_bay_conductor tests

Tests that were testing specific COE behaviour have been spun out into
their own class. test_bay_conductor was over 1000 lines long, breaking
this file down allows easier understanding the code base and reduces
complexity.

Change-Id: I290ba02569e0a44bc30e38b9b34b2dbf9204d68a
Closes-Bug: #1506455

subject: Allow deleting policy by name
messages:
[{'account_id': 11278, 'date': '2015-09-28 04:52:10.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 1.'}, {'account_id': 11278, 'date': '2015-09-28 05:00:35.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Commit message was updated'}, {'account_id': 11278, 'date': '2015-09-28 05:51:22.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Commit message was updated'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-09-28 06:20:32.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Verified+1

Build succeeded (check pipeline).

- gate-congress-pep8 http://logs.openstack.org/00/228300/3/check/gate-congress-pep8/78fe3c0/ : SUCCESS in 2m 42s

- gate-congress-dsvm-api http://logs.openstack.org/00/228300/3/check/gate-congress-dsvm-api/8a76c25/ : SUCCESS in 29m 03s'}, {'account_id': 8215, 'date': '2015-09-28 16:19:13.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Code-Review+1

Letting others comment'}, {'account_id': 8276, 'date': '2015-09-30 06:43:56.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3: Code-Review-1

Actually I don't want to very much to support deleting resource by name in Congress server side. That make the API and internal logic very hard to be maintained.

For any methods, we don't know whether the argument is id or name, so we must try to get_by_id at first, if the result is None, try to get_by_name again, like your code do. It isn't graceful at all. 

For any APIs, the input should be no ambiguity, when we delete policy, the REST API is:

DELETE /policies/<policy_id>

So we should only support delete by id in Congress server side.

If we want to implement the feature that delete policy by name, I think the python-congressclient should be a right place, list policies by name, get policy id, then delete policy by id."}, {'account_id': 11278, 'date': '2015-09-30 07:18:07.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

Thanks Rui Chen for the review. 

But I don't quite agree with your argument. All the other congress commands, support listing by policy name. As policy name is also a unique identifier it does no harm in supporting that and is more user friendly compared to id.

It will confuse more users if we don't support only delete command by name, and for all others we do.

As you suggested, it can be handled in client side also. But I refrained from doing so, as we are making 2 API calls for one request (one for listing all policies , other for deleting the policy). So, I felt handling the logic on server side would be the more optimized way as we have all data in hand.

wdyt?"}, {'account_id': 8878, 'date': '2015-09-30 07:52:39.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3: Code-Review-1

(4 comments)

IMO, that's good idea that Congress allows user to retrieve policies by its name if possible. I, however, have some concerns about the feature. Please see the comments."}, {'account_id': 8276, 'date': '2015-09-30 09:06:00.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

I don't think all the congress commands support deleting by name, deleting datasource/policy/rule API only support deleting by id, and showing policy detail API only support showing by policy id too.

I still think we should implement deleting by name in python-congressclient side, and the util method utils.get_resource_id_from_name() had been implemented in python-congressclient, please refer to deleting datasource/rule in client code.

And I want to point out that if the argument of method isn't sure (id or name), we must query database twice to get the result, right?"}, {'account_id': 8215, 'date': '2015-10-02 16:03:11.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

I think we should support deletion (and other operations) by name on the server when the name is guaranteed to uniquely identify the resource.'}, {'account_id': 8215, 'date': '2015-10-02 16:08:18.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

I'd actually be more in favor of having the server ONLY accept the policy name than having the server ONLY accept the policy UUID.  The policy name will ALWAYS uniquely identify the policy--that assumption is built into the policy language itself.   At some point, we were using human-friendly strings as the ID field, but then someone thought it would be confusing to users and created the NAME and ID fields."}, {'account_id': 8215, 'date': '2015-10-02 16:17:29.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Code-Review-1

(3 comments)'}, {'account_id': 8878, 'date': '2015-10-05 01:30:22.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

(1 comment)'}, {'account_id': 11278, 'date': '2015-10-05 04:14:16.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

(2 comments)'}, {'account_id': 11278, 'date': '2015-10-05 05:15:46.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 4.'}, {'account_id': 11278, 'date': '2015-10-05 05:19:10.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

Tim, Masahito, Thanks for the review. I tried to address your comments in patch set 4. Let me know if it addresses your concerns.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-10-05 05:48:05.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4: Verified+1

Build succeeded (check pipeline).

- gate-congress-pep8 http://logs.openstack.org/00/228300/4/check/gate-congress-pep8/096b461/ : SUCCESS in 2m 33s

- gate-congress-dsvm-api http://logs.openstack.org/00/228300/4/check/gate-congress-dsvm-api/5ad6262/ : SUCCESS in 32m 13s'}, {'account_id': 8276, 'date': '2015-10-08 08:44:22.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

Actually, I don't oppose the API that delete policy by name, I oppose that we prepare to support deleting policy by name and unid in one API at the same time.

ONLY by uuid or ONLY by name is good, but not both.

I think the arguments "id_or_name" and the logic "if id exist elif name exist" are difficult to understand and maintain. As a developer, I hope the method arguments and API aren't ambiguity.'}, {'account_id': 8878, 'date': '2015-10-08 14:03:23.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4: Code-Review+1

(1 comment)

The logic looks good to me. I think the error message isn't correct, so please tweak it if possible."}, {'account_id': 8215, 'date': '2015-10-14 18:06:32.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4: Code-Review-1

commit_message:
admin not able to set maintenance state for volume

In admin volume table, maintenance state was not able
to set by admin via horizon. since the option is not
present in the choice list.

The status is added in the display choices also to
show the translated status.

This patch adding the new maintenance state in the
choice list.

Change-Id: I11c3845fb95093db08c5a0fdb568dd06b7370841
Closes-Bug: #1490559

[{'created': '2015-09-23 12:12:21.000000000', 'message': 'Remove quotes from subshell call in bash script

Always no quotes for $() statement.

We don't need quotes to hold blanks in result:
 # i=$(echo 1 2 3)
 # echo $i
 1 2 3
 #

These quotes can make something wrong in some case:
 # i=$(echo '!')
 #
 # i="$(echo '!')"
 -bash: !: event not found
 #

No real problem for current code, only to use a better code style.

Change-Id: Iabb98ba4db4f04b4f10c944184356dab648af3a6
Signed-off-by: Zhao Lei <zhaolei@cn.fujitsu.com>
'}]
commit_message:
Remove quotes from subshell call in bash script

Always no quotes for $() statement.

We don't need quotes to hold blanks in result:
 # i=$(echo 1 2 3)
 # echo $i
 1 2 3
 #

These quotes can make something wrong in some case:
 # i=$(echo '!')
 #
 # i="$(echo '!')"
 -bash: !: event not found
 #

No real problem for current code, only to use a better code style.

Change-Id: Iabb98ba4db4f04b4f10c944184356dab648af3a6
Signed-off-by: Zhao Lei <zhaolei@cn.fujitsu.com>

commit_message:
Add -constraints sections for base CI jobs

Using factors with sections is not a thing and likely will not be for
a while, as such we are going to have to duplicate sections to be able
to set the constraints based install_command.

Implements Blueprint: Requirements-Management

Change-Id: Ie679904330a83e4b7eb75c189b48afef127b0d22

commit_message:
Sqush requirements and post-versioning

Several tests are failing with:
    ValueError: git history requires a target version of
    pbr.version.SemanticVersion(5.0.1), but target version is
    pbr.version.SemanticVersion(5.0.0)

Review Ic7a15c251084fb62a5dbaf659489cefeca7ca310
is supposed to fix that, however it's being blocked by oslo.messageing
2.6.0 and 2.6.1

Manually sync requirements including banning the 2 oslo.messageing
releases, and switch to post-versioning.

Change-Id: I9d6f77082febfd7e916586f3a350b836a00df38c
Closes-Bug: 1506805
Co-Authored-By: Thierry Carrez <thierry@openstack.org>

commit_message:
Add Local cache documentation for Oracle ZFSSA Cinder drivers.

This patch adds documentation of the Local cache feature for Oracle ZFSSA iSCSI
and NFS Cinder drivers.

Change-Id: I2324cdc559f14c1bd52500d5a62a4c8401294018
Closes-Bug: 1504262

commit_message:
Remove retry decorator as neutron has moved them into api layer

The following change: Ifffd424b693f57b5dd3de4dc625b50acc23abe0f
moves these decorators to the api layer so we no longer need them
in the plugin.

Change-Id: I33689769005149aae616cd56349771b2d540b19f

commit_message:
Add shallow syntax checking

`bash -n` will do a shallow syntax check on a bash script,
just checking that the script parses. It's possible to have
scripts that pass all bashate style checks, but don't actually
run because of a syntax error, so this adds error code E040
and reports the syntax errors that `bash -n` outputs.

Change-Id: Ib128c54493221e71cca19a497a6efc4f5fc368c1

commit_message:
Adding IQN to the glossary

Abbreviation of IQN is not easy to understand,
add a description about it.Document containing
the glossary, for example:

doc/admin-guide-cloud/source/ts_non_existent_host.rst
doc/admin-guide-cloud/source/ts_cinder_config.rst
doc/admin-guide-cloud/source/ts-duplicate-3par-host.rst
doc/admin-guide-cloud/source/blockstorage-manage-volumes.rst

Change-Id: Ia9588d4f2e081f2b7d8f6a63286c9fdbf60f6a96

commit_message:
Add affinity/anti-affinity documentation

This patch documents the affinity and anti-affinity
features in Cinder that allow admins some control
over volume scheduling.

Change-Id: I23404f5974c0e03fca7bdb0af0f8a49644258fed
Closes-Bug: #1342628

commit_message:
Block oslo.messaging 2.6.1 release

The oslo.messaging-2.6.1 has broken Ceilometer Jenkins job two days, The
change[1] could hopefully fix the issue, but it is better to block the
oslo.messaging-2.6.1 to make Ceilometer Jenkins alive now.

[1] https://review.openstack.org/#/c/234372/

Related-Bug: #1505730
Change-Id: Id1e58a9db0d277de2f30de54db97040811f40ff2
(cherry picked from commit 71e57cdd035f64f8eedf36a2e9de011551a4c910)

commit_message:
Make node related DB queries project safe

This patch makes all node related DB query interfaces project
safe by default.

Change-Id: I92fb60bef0892f95869dc7c98bd56635ce8c92bc
Implements: blueprint make-db-query-project-safe

add a placement-policy to enable vSphere DRS functions

Provide a flexible way to control affinity and unti-affinity placement
of different nodes or node groups on vSphere clusters.

Change-Id: I84c7be8b8e80c0ee3287b00b57faf68190325124

commit_message:
Make to_dict method work for deleted cluster

Currently, to_dict method doesn't work correctly for deleted cluster
since the profile of cluster could have been deleted and thus fail
the runtime data loading. This patch fixes this issue.

Change-Id: Ie34c1ef346f7ecf2c1963796375cf304ef397102

subject: Add a TODO item
messages:
[{'account_id': 11034, 'date': '2015-10-13 08:35:42.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 1.'}, {'account_id': 8246, 'date': '2015-10-13 09:24:29.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: Code-Review+2

It is okay to enforce multi-tenancy as what other projects have been doing. My only concern is whether that always holds true. There could be requests to share a profile across projects?

I don't have a clear thought on how to best handle this. Maybe the 'permission' field should be added to all objects so that we can have a finer granular access control?

Anyway, this change is at least something we can do for the moment. I'm not against it."}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-10-13 10:22:13.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Verified+1

Sounds good to me. It's a model that is already adopted by services within OpenStack, so I see no big negative in trying to follow the crowd here."}, {'account_id': 11034, 'date': '2015-10-14 02:23:36.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

Understand your concern. I think we can add permission check in DB interfaces to enable profile sharing cross different projects/users. IMHO, applying permission to all objects is an acceptable(although might be interim) solution to provide access privilege control in Senlin before Keystone can provide thorough support for role-based privilege checking. Will think it through.'}, {'account_id': 7404, 'date': '2015-10-14 15:13:53.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review+1'}, {'account_id': 11034, 'date': '2015-10-19 02:00:14.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review+2 Workflow+1'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-10-19 02:00:20.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: -Verified

commit_message:
Add python-swiftclient as a dependency

We optionally depend on python-swiftclient if it is being used as a
backing data store, so lets add it to our requirements rather than have
our users deal with a stacktrace.

Change-Id: I6d3cea689fb1aa9308fc6b574543fc48194da8a1

commit_message:
Add 'uplink' type driver

This patch adds the 'uplink' type driver, so that uplink type
networks may be created with the ml2 plugin and the midonet
ml2 driver.

Change-Id: I15cba5467fd4f470e316f8aab16254fe846e6a48
Co-Authored-By: Ryu Ishimoto <ryu@midokura.com>

commit_message:
LVM: Support a volume-group on shared storage

This proposal enables direct I/O path from VMs to storage using LVM driver
with LVM on shared storage volume. By enabling direct I/O path provides
stable I/O path for VMs and improve throughput to VMs.

In this feature, both Nova and Cinder pieces are necessary.

Change-Id: I95fe79432a96496dbcd8b50fe8f906d52784adce
Implements: blueprint lvm-driver-for-shared-storage

commit_message:
Standardize federated auth token scoping

For a greater standardization it is advised to use auth method
``token``. That being said, ``Saml2ScopedTokenMethod`` as well as
corresponding entry point are being removed.

Change-Id: I16f90f9b1ae0e54113f7f7158df1911d2c4d7b0c
Partially-Implements: bp standardize-federated-tokens-scoping

commit_message:
Remove unnecessary update_replace parameter

For tests in AutoScalingGroupUpdatePolicyTest, update_replace happens
based on the changes to properties(ImageId vs InstanceType) and
update_replace parameter is not used.

Change-Id: I72c7e81dd29693c4cf90c64f37911a529f65d541

commit_message:
Add environment varible to skip amp image build

This patch adds an environment variable check in the devstack
plugin.sh script that disables the amphora image build process.
This will be used by gate test jobs that test against the noop
driver and do not boot amphora.

Change-Id: I6faf2f4d853972f7e700122444da202bdba2dc64

commit_message:
Fix so that we build tripleo-puppet-elements pkgs

The previous "puppet" regex was matching the tripleo-puppet-elements
project meaning that we don't actually build puppet packages.

Change-Id: I7d3d389843eae8738de8b346806147a5826bb60f

The issue is that coverage must be calling os.path.exists() while covering the code that also calls os.path.exists(). This means that your mock ends up showing it was called elsewhere. Not sure why we would exclude coverage 4.0 for this, just fix the test (one possible method is check all calls against the mocked out lib).

The problem with excluding coverage is that I don't think it is fair to say coverage cannot call things like os.path.exists because you want to mock it."}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-10-02 01:31:46.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Verified-1

- gate-requirements-tox-validate http://logs.openstack.org/81/228581/3/check/gate-requirements-tox-validate/6af4f7a/ : SUCCESS in 35s'}, {'account_id': 10850, 'date': '2015-10-02 21:16:30.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Code-Review+1

Clark, you are making our case for us: "The issue is that coverage must be calling os.path.exists() while covering the code that also calls os.path.exists()." A test framework needs to be transparent to the code it's testing. If I want to mock os.path.exists() in my tests the test/coverage frame work should allow me to do that.  Since version 3.0 doesn't have that problem I am with Michael to exclude that version.'}, {'account_id': 4146, 'date': '2015-10-05 22:10:17.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

I disagree, in this case being transparent would mean not accounting for coverage on os.path.exists because coverage itself calls it. I don't think that is the problem here. Your mock is invasive to python stdlib and any other lib/thread/etc could trip this behavior.

I really think for this specific case just fixing the test is easiest particularly after we have made many changes across openstack to make latest coverage viable."}, {'account_id': 10850, 'date': '2015-10-05 22:36:02.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

"Your mock is invasive to python stdlib" We use @mock.patch exclusively which scopes it to our test code. So again I would expect a coverage framework to be ok with that.'}, {'account_id': 10850, 'date': '2015-10-06 02:50:36.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

I reviewed the code added in coverage https://bitbucket.org/ned/coveragepy/commits/d9c39196e83f4895abec1fa054dcc09627ce5c9c and it seems he is instrumenting the code under test with a call to os.path.exists -- it stands to reason that a coverage framework should be very defensive when using any calls which might be mocked by the code under test. So we will monitor the situation closely and see if the coverage code gets changed to be more defensive or if we need to make amends ro accommodate the coverage changes --'}, {'account_id': 11628, 'date': '2015-10-06 15:43:26.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

A fix has been posted to the coverage repository:
https://bitbucket.org/ned/coveragepy/commits/f5724e58bfed

This resolves the issues we saw in Octavia with the 4.0 release.'}, {'account_id': 10850, 'date': '2015-10-06 15:47:59.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

Yeah!! So let's abandon that patch!"}, {'account_id': 11628, 'date': '2015-10-06 16:01:47.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

We still need this to merge as a release of coverage with the fix has not yet occurred.  Version 4.0 of coverage is known bad and should be excluded.'}, {'account_id': 4146, 'date': '2015-10-07 23:29:12.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

Reading the coverage patch only os is affected by the fix sys, json, socket, re, etc are all still possibly in this boat. It seems odd to consider this fixed in that case when any mocks of those other stdlib modules would have to be defensive as well.

Do we really want to exclude every version of coverage that trips up any of these potentially mocked items? I really do think that our tests have to be smarter if we expect coverage to cover the tests.'}, {'account_id': 11628, 'date': '2015-10-09 18:55:43.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

I agree with you that coverage should add defensive code to all of the imports that are being used in the code it is injecting into the code under test.  That way it would not be impacting the ability to fully test user code.  I communicated this idea to the developer that was working on this fix and I hope that it will be implemented widely in a future update.

I however don't understand how we can effectively make our tests "smarter".  In this case coverage added an import to code they inject into our test code without protecting it from interacting with our code and test code.  The tests this regression caused to fail are valid tests that check to make sure the code properly handles the presence of files, such as security certificates being generated in one case, correctly. 

Until coverage is fully updated to not impact the code under test I see no other option than to exclude versions that have regressions that break existing tests.'}, {'account_id': 11628, 'date': '2015-10-18 23:17:58.000000000', 'content': 'Abandoned

This has now been fixed upstream.'}]

commit_message:
Exclude coverage 4.0

Octavia is seeing test failures with coverage 4.0 that do not
appear when run without coverage or with the previous release.

Please Note: This is not related to the ignore-errors ->
ignore_errors issue previously corrected.

Upstream coverage bug:  https://bitbucket.org/ned/coveragepy/issues/416/coverage-40-is-causing-existing-unit-tests

Change-Id: I5c9790d441596c6b925cd5a36ba03b354795eee0

commit_message:
Remove deprecated glance_store opts from default section

The glance store opts should be specified in the glance_store
section. We had deprecated the opts in default section in Juno.

DocImpact

Change-Id: Ib0fda16d7f00f6f3ff15eeae87615aec26efaaac

[{'created': '2015-10-16 07:37:03.000000000', 'message': 'Put swift {account,container,object} logs where they belong

The pattern for nova and neutron on hosts is to have a symlink from

commit_message:
Put swift {account,container,object} logs where they belong

The pattern for nova and neutron on hosts is to have a symlink from
/var/log/{service} to /openstack/log/_hostname_-{service}/ and then
to have all the service logs configured to log to /var/log/{service}
as that is a logical place for an operator to look for them.

Swift currently does not follow that pattern.

Currently the swift {account,container,object} logs are placed in
/openstack/log/{hostname}/, whereas the proxy logs are placed in
/var/log/swift/. On hosts the /var/log/swift symlink to
/openstack/log/{hostname}-swift/ is created, but not used.

This creates confusion for operators trying to find the logs in the
logical (and upstream) pattern in the directory /var/log/{service}.

This patch puts the swift logs where they belong.

Upgrade Notes:
 - This changes the location of the log storage on swift hosts from
   /openstack/log/{hostname} to /openstack/log/{hostname}-swift
 - Any log processing or monitoring tooling that consumes swift logs
   will need to be adjusted to consume them from the new location,
   or simply to consume them from /var/log/swift

DocImpact
UpgradeImpact
Closes-Bug: #1417536
Change-Id: I8d6ec98d310ce8d4e4a7a6cc5fb2d349d17757cf

commit_message:
Add check for Flask app debug=True usage

When executed with debug=True, Flask applications expose the Werkzeug
debugger which includes an abritrary code execution function.

This check looks for a combination of the flask module being imported,
a .run() call, and a named argument debug=True.

Setting it up in plugins/app_debug.py so we can add checks for Django
and perhaps other frameworks in future.

Change-Id: If49e53d0807dfc2fccad6433edc5ef43f5464f22
Implements: blueprint detect-werkzeug-debug-enabled

commit_message:
Mark XML API as deprecated in Mitaka.

Cinder XML API is untested and will be removed in the N release.

Implements: blueprint deprecate-xml-api
Change-Id: I753dedadf99bbb8e49d0076aa0da4ffa4ff97a4b

commit_message:
Store RabbitMQ cert/key in config dir

Storing rabbit's private key in /etc/ssl/private causes problems since that
directory (and the files within it) can only be accessed by root on Ubuntu
systems. Storing the key within the RabbitMQ configuration directory would
allow the key to be read by the 'rabbitmq' user.

The key can also be set to mode 0600 as well by moving its location and
changing it to be owned by the rabbitmq user.

Closes-bug: 1506992

Change-Id: Iede0748b57a86b33879d759505dd8f80476b574c

commit_message:
Do not copy sources

We do not need to copy source files anymore with current
openstackdocstheme, unset html_show_sourcelink and html_copy_source
links. Report a bug works without these as well.

This reduces the amount of files we build and publish (for Install Guide
from 42 MB to 39 MB), and thus speeds up building (from 44 to 41s for
Install Guide) slightly.

Change-Id: I316b023fae8ac5ccdbc3436bc68d00cafa9dc571

commit_message:
Allow to specify number of retries for puppet task

Now it's possible to specify a number of retries for
puppet task in granural deployment by specifying a new
parameter "retries":

  parameters:
    ...
    retries: 10

By default, there are 2 retries.

Change-Id: I819a019cf488fc1bd0d52b35d1693fcc088125cb
Partial-Bug: #1457794
(cherry picked from commit d89ea8c3c6d91e3c5151534f4145b50c45b25d13)

commit_message:
Change support_status to HIDDEN in res props

There are some resources' properties, where deprecation cycle
is over, so there's necessity to add translation rules for
such properties and change their support_status to HIDDEN.

For information about deprecation process read Heat docs [1].

[1] http://docs.openstack.org/developer/heat/supportstatus.html

Change-Id: I60e5ba28e89333faff263915a568a5e4d8f09505

line with the upstream configuration file to make comparing them

commit_message:
Fix to correctly set the cinder_storage_address

This change sets the cinder storage address based on the
facts the play is able to set about the environment.

This will correct configure the iscsi address within cinder
to use the correct network which is not always the default
container address.

Change-Id: I647161c0154cad11bf2f31b6b7cd8476e0662f12
Closes-Bug: #1504208
Signed-off-by: Kevin Carter <kevin.carter@rackspace.com>

commit_message:
Fix list-availability-zones API for PostgreSQL

Listing of availability zones using PostgreSQl does not work in Manila.
It is caused by usage of not strict types comparison.
So, fix it and add Tempest test for API.

Change-Id: I21a064d60c4e1ccb6752ba6e220785f80bd1cb69
Closes-Bug: #1506938

commit_message:
Add a scenario to test LMA 0.7

Renamed deploy_lma_collector_ha into deploy_lma_toolchain and
added deploy_lma_toolchain_0_7 scenario that can be used
with the branch stable/0.7 of LMA. For the master branch of LMA
you need to use deploy_lma_toolchain.

Change-Id: I456c4227d19f87576903af5c20334098963e3832

commit_message:
Port rpc and wsgi to Python 3

* rpc: allow also exceptions from the builtins module. On Python 3,
  builtin exceptions are part of the builtins module. The exceptions
  module was removed in Python 3.
* Fix usage of reraise(): translate_exception() returns an instance
  which is the second parameter of the reraise() function, not the
  first parameter. The first parameter is the exception type.
* test_rpc: add json_dump_as_bytes() helper to serialize JSON as
  bytes.
* JSONRequestDeserializer: don't compare None to int, it raises a
  TypeError on Python 3.
* Fix Unicode versus bytes issues: HTTP body type is bytes. Encode
  JSON to UTF-8 for example. Replace StringIO with BytesIO.
* Replace filter() with a list-comprehension to get a list on
  Python 3.
* test_client, test_image_cache_client: use bytes for HTTP body.
* tox.ini: add glance.tests.unit.common.test_rpc to Python 3.

Change-Id: I9960d6a810375474f89c1788b7016a8fbb0770e0

commit_message:
Add option to run_tempest.sh to save subunit output

This can be used for mechanical inspection, e.g. for
example by rally or other post-analysis tools.

Change-Id: I77b31936aa0fc86e062520422c3a41191cc2dfdf

commit_message:
Implementing port-chain functionality

This patch implements port-chain feature E2E addressing
below functionalities.
 - API/DB/Plugin implementation of port-chain interface.
 - API/DB/Plugin implementation of flow-classifier interface.
 - OVS Driver implementation for realising port-chain.

APIImpact

Outstanding Items:
 - Unit testing for driver code.
 - API/Full-stack testing

Change-Id: I82a87e3ae633aab03be02a90907975c42634cac3
Co-Authored-By: Louis Fourie <louis.fourie@huawei.com>
Co-Authored-By: vikram.choudhary <vikram.choudhary@huawei.com>

commit_message:
Decrease test failure if second changes during run

test_create_with_live_time fails gating constantly. This is due to
the logic in the test which breaks if the second changes between the
two timestamps expires_at and updated_at are created. This change
drops the failure rate to those occasions where we hit that second
change also to minute change.

Closes-Bug: #1505675

Change-Id: I234d80388edd2a659a2374a29179ce23b23bb99a
(cherry picked from commit b413db7652d6edc22e0c15922b6df1c7acc6b177)

commit_message:
Minor fixes in networking-guide

- Some files contain <feff> BOM at the beginning of files,
  but they are unnecessary. This commit removes them.
- Rename deploy_scenario4b.rst -> scenario_provider_lb.rst
  Filenames of all other scenarios are "scenario_*.rst" and
  deploy_scenario4b.rst was an exception.

Change-Id: I8f40266c3291bb66d734d9b71add1e151a4c3742

commit_message:
Pass CONF to logging setup

The function accepts two parameters, the first one being the
current CONF. The second parameter is the product name.

Closes-bug: #1505710

commit_message:
Fixed registry invalid token exception handling

When the registry has an error validating the token that the api
has sent it a 500 is returned rather than 401. This fix catches the
NotAuthenticated exception and throws an HTTPUnauthorized instead.

Change-Id: I405cd98346e2df06c02e37bfdf903a54a29f7b19
Closes-bug:1504184

commit_message:
Merge tag '7.0.0'

This is a null-merge of the 7.0.0 release tag back into the master
branch so that the 7.0.0 tag will appear in the git commit history of
the master branch. It contains no actual changes to the master branch,
regardless of how our code review system's UI represents it. Please
ask in #openstack-infra if you have any questions, and otherwise try
to merge this as quickly as possible to avoid later conflicts on the
master branch.

Change-Id: Icaa0f7eae22bcd886a5f6867d688ee90ae0a406c

[{'created': '2015-02-19 00:25:00.000000000', 'message': 'WIP - Functional tests for catalog index service

An initial pass at functional tests for the catalog index service.
Adds to the existing functional tests to run a glance-graffiti server,
as well as an elasticsearch server if present on the test system.

The elasticsearch server will run on a randomized port, and it uses
a temporary directory for its data storage. Tests should create and
tear down any indices they use. It runs with a minimal memory
configuration and assumes elasticsearch to be present on the test
system.

The initial tests include one RBAC test and one test of an indexing edge
case, and will need expanding upon.

Implements: blueprint catalog-index-service
Change-Id: I2dd8f67bb8a2a4125c4dd54afa2ffd0400a1dce2

commit_message:
WIP - Functional tests for catalog index service

An initial pass at functional tests for the catalog index service.
Since test_search is the only class that tests SearchServer, I have
not added it to the list in start_servers.

The elasticsearch server runs on a randomized port, and it uses
a temporary directory for its data storage. Tests should create and
tear down any indices they use (at least until the server ensures
that mappings are applied at startup). It runs with a minimal memory
configuration and currently assumes elasticsearch to be present on the test
system.

Tests include general expected error conditions, RBAC tests for the two
current plugins and property protection tests for glance images.

Implements: blueprint catalog-index-service
Change-Id: I2dd8f67bb8a2a4125c4dd54afa2ffd0400a1dce2

commit_message:
Only use LOG.exception in exception handler

There were a few instances of the code calling LOG.exception
in places where there was not an exception in context. This
can cause errors and should just be LOG.error as it effectively
ends up being.

Some instances in vhdutils.py are being left as they are being
addressed in Ib3113f2c4752d37e890f97d259da5d51cbfcfb96 under a
different bug report.

Change-Id: I1898c4d63c16c4d41b3e255a7de21429d1b04ddb
Closes-bug: #1504735

commit_message:
Port API to Python 3

* test_make_flat_dict(): only use one dictionary key. On Python 3,
  the hash function is now randomized by default and so dictionary
  keys are returned in a random order.
* Replace "not cmp(a, b) == 0" with "a != b"
* test_common: replace range(n) with list(range(n)) to get a list on
  Python 3. On Python 3, range() now returns an iterator.
* Replace dict.items()[0] with list(dict.items()[0]). On Python 3,
  dict.items() now returns a view which is not indexable.
* VolumeTypesController.index(): replace dict.values() with
  list(dict.values()) to get a list on Python 3.
* test_xmlutil: use byte strings for XML
* test_extensions: use byte strings for HTTP body
* Add the following tests to tests-py3.txt:

  - cinder.tests.unit.api.test_common
  - cinder.tests.unit.api.test_extensions
  - cinder.tests.unit.api.test_versions
  - cinder.tests.unit.api.test_xmlutil

Partial-Implements: blueprint cinder-python3
Change-Id: I40c28f6b6a1cf72ce13774755153c8691b4d621b

commit_message:
Improve README contents

Add more information in README.rst

Include
* showing the latest package version and download count on top
* list source links relative to murano like PyPi, Launchpad project,
Blueprints, Bugs, Source, Specs, and How to Contribute.

commit_message:
Change paths for renamed projects

On Oct. 17th the stackforge namespace will be retired.

This patch updates the paths for those projects formly on
stackforge moving to the openstack namespace.

Not to be merged prior to Oct. 17th.

This patch also catches a few stragglers that were renamed prior
to Oct. 17th but the paths were never updated for stable/juno.

Change-Id: Ide8948a538926bc1cba9608eb918fe4cc47746d3

commit_message:
Stackforge projects are now read-only

Stackforge has been retired as a namespace. Any projects
remaining in the stackforge namespace are retired.

This patch makes them all read-only by deleted all acls in
gerrit/acls/stackforge and pointing all remaining projects at
the lone new acl file for stackforge retired.config, which is
set to read-only permissions.

Change-Id: I9336323f52006e7cf856e797a2013456c214fd73

commit_message:
Change paths for renamed projects

On Oct. 17th the stackforge namespace will be retired.

This patch updates the paths for those projects formly on
stackforge moving to the openstack namespace.

Not to be merged prior to Oct. 17th.

Change-Id: I033d5ec856fbab450fa3b022b646ea640b38b402

commit_message:
Validate Generic Signature

The validation API allows to validate a generic signature in a
request without returning a token.

If the signature is valid a 201 response is returned and a 401 if
the signature is invalid.

Change-Id: I96ef2c537eab5ae6f16a5e1f246474daeef20225

commit_message:
Stackforge namespace retirement renaming

This patch renames many projects that were in the stackforge namespace
and moves them to the openstack namespace.

Input for this process was derived from community collaboration
resulting in this set of two lists:
https://wiki.openstack.org/w/index.php?title=Stackforge_Namespace_Retirement&oldid=92717

Uses data/stackforge-renames in patchset 36 of
https://review.openstack.org/#/c/228002/
as input to the script in patchset 36 of
https://review.openstack.org/#/c/228002/

Change-Id: I5d41b8268b9472aef78dce810ac30ee959ae8d42

commit_message:
Fix silent iSCSI login failures

This patch fixes an issue where every iSCSI login attempt fails
and the code doesn't raise an exception.  It used to silently fail
with nothing but a log warning.

The iSCSI connector now checks to make sure that at least 1 of the
N potential target portals login attempts is successful.

Change-Id: Id248c3f1b12385c9d26150c6aa9dd504c01d0df8
Closes-Bug: #1464988

commit_message:
encryption_api_url requires a version

If the value configured for encryption_api_url does not include the
barbican API version, then some calls from cinder will fail. This can
mean that encrypted volumes cannot be deleted. To prevent this happening
raise an exception if the configured value for encryption_api_url does not
include the barbican version.

Change-Id: I1a4c9b9e93d7d189a3cdf1469e8bb87817473da5
Closes-Bug: #1501780

commit_message:
Make floating IP func tests less racey

The resource string should not be shared across tests. This could
cause bad things. Also, change a CIDR used in a test to something
less used.

Change-Id: I47a32b5b10ebc9096a816d2430387234fbe97cef

commit_message:
Make router func tests less racey

Some tests were sharing the same code that created a subnet.
This could cause problems if the tests were to run concurrently.
Avoid that by making each test specify the subnet CIDR it wants.

Change-Id: I0a4f8913af8f8069fc86f168cda35495553aee09

commit_message:
put old run-upgrade script back

This commit puts the original run-upgrade script back in place as
run-upgrade-old.sh

Whilst the new script is undoubtedly better, the original script should
remain in tree to be used by deployers who may have built some tooling
around it.

Closes Bug: #1506788

Change-Id: Iad783c07ef746463e2b52be4bc9857bd63993691

fix image_ref attr in gnocchi resource

image_ref attr should match to image_ref in metadata, not image_ref_url

Closes-Bug: #1506595

[{'created': '2015-10-08 18:24:00.000000000', 'message': 'NetApp volume/snapshot delete performance fix

cDOT NFS NetApp drivers back cinder volumes with array-side files and
use array-side cloning techniques when creating snapshots and when
creating volumes from glance images.  Customers have experienced
performance issues on the array when deleting many of these in
in quick succession, especially for large volumes.

This commit addresses these performance issues by overriding parent
class volume and snapshot delete methods, which use OS "rm" command to
delete volume backing files, with methods that use DOT API to delete
these files, and which invoke the optimized file deletion engine
available in DOT 8.3.

Closes-bug: 1497258
Change-Id: I44428d0840f6584f93ca214a2a607869b345554c
(cherry picked from commit 4163fb29add1f3c80cb902c8735be3dde24930d3)

commit_message:
NetApp volume/snapshot delete performance fix

cDOT NFS NetApp drivers back cinder volumes with array-side files and
use array-side cloning techniques when creating snapshots and when
creating volumes from glance images.  Customers have experienced
performance issues on the array when deleting many of these in
in quick succession, especially for large volumes.

This commit addresses these performance issues by overriding parent
class volume and snapshot delete methods, which use OS "rm" command to
delete volume backing files, with methods that use DOT API to delete
these files, and which invoke the optimized file deletion engine
available in DOT 8.3.

Note that some unit tests were not backported since they depended on
modules not available in kilo.

Closes-bug: 1497258
(cherry picked from commit 4163fb29add1f3c80cb902c8735be3dde24930d3)

Conflicts:
	cinder/tests/volume/drivers/netapp/dataontap/fakes.py

Change-Id: I44428d0840f6584f93ca214a2a607869b345554c

The reason I rename 'namespace' to 'repository' is that avoid to the meaning of namespace in build.py flag, kolla-ansible, Dockerfile.

By the way, in the document, docker use username instead of namespace.
https://docs.docker.com/reference/commandline/tag/"}, {'account_id': 13747, 'date': '2015-10-15 07:01:29.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

[{'created': '2015-10-14 08:26:20.000000000', 'message': 'add "registry" flag to "tools/build.py"

With registry flag,
build image using `tools/build.py --registry 172.22.2.81:4000`
the image name looks like `172.22.2.81:4000/kollaglue/data`
When user use kolla-ansible,
user set `docker_registry` to `172.22.2.81:4000` in `/etc/kolla/globals.yml`.

Build image using `tools/build.py -n abcd`
the image name looks like `abcd/data`
When user use kolla-ansible,
user set `docker_namespace:` to `abcd` in `/etc/kolla/globals.yml`.

build image using `tools/build.py -n abcd --registry 172.22.2.81:4000`
the image name looks like `abcd/data`
When user use kolla-ansible,
user set `docker_namespace:` to `abcd` in `/etc/kolla/globals.yml`.
user set `docker_registry` to `172.22.2.81:4000` in `/etc/kolla/globals.yml`.

With the feature, it will reduce user confusing and mistaking.

Change-Id: I18ac7a3ccec032888e35f5e9a79fc190760cc8a0
Closes-Bug: #1505056

commit_message:
add "registry" flag to "tools/build.py"

With registry flag,
build image using `tools/build.py --registry 172.22.2.81:4000`
the image name looks like `172.22.2.81:4000/kollaglue/data`
When user use kolla-ansible,
user set `docker_registry` to `172.22.2.81:4000` in `/etc/kolla/globals.yml`.

Build image using `tools/build.py -n abcd`
the image name looks like `abcd/data`
When user use kolla-ansible,
user set `docker_namespace:` to `abcd` in `/etc/kolla/globals.yml`.

build image using `tools/build.py -n abcd --registry 172.22.2.81:4000`
the image name looks like `abcd/data`
When user use kolla-ansible,
user set `docker_namespace:` to `abcd` in `/etc/kolla/globals.yml`.
user set `docker_registry` to `172.22.2.81:4000` in `/etc/kolla/globals.yml`.

With the feature, it will reduce user confusing and mistaking.

Change-Id: I18ac7a3ccec032888e35f5e9a79fc190760cc8a0
Closes-Bug: #1505056

Implements blueprint: integration-tests-hardening
Change-Id: I3f92ef4cfd098d080199350cbf5e6061aa050907

commit_message:
Do not match table actions by ordering in integration tests

Instead of this match them by action <a> tag's id, which is composed:
* from table name, fixed part and action name for table-level actions and
* from row id, fixed part and action name for row-level actions.

Doing so may make action names in page objects less readable as they
have to be the same as real object name (which are rather terse).

Implements blueprint: integration-tests-hardening
Change-Id: I3f92ef4cfd098d080199350cbf5e6061aa050907

commit_message:
Volume extend error does not catch exception

Volume extension API does not throw HTTPBadRequest response,
when input to the API is invalid.
This patch handles invalid input to the volume extension API
and return HTTPBadRequest.

APIImpact
Change-Id: I93e81514c9c1bea9fa80cfb14c5f1d4b00dd0c28

commit_message:
Fix method VolumeTypeList.get_all

Function volume_types.get_all_types returns dict, then
VolumeTypeList.get_all passes it to base.obj_make_list, which, in turn,
passes it to oslo_versionedobjects.base.obj_make_list.

And this function iterates over 4th argument and calls
item_cls._from_db_object for each item. So if it will iterate over dict
from volume_types.get_all_types, it'll get strings instead of orm
objects.

By the way, VolumeTypeList.get_all is not used anywhere in cinder code.
I tried to use it in unit test for my new patch and found this problem.

Closes-Bug: #1505653

Change-Id: If789bc5bf224974de5c4e4b9a57c83ef51d1779b

commit_message:
Fix updating only volume type is_public

When updating only volume type is_public, error will be raised: `ERROR:
Specify either volume type name and/or description`. Fixed this by
adding a check that is_public is None, the same way name and description
do.

APIImpact
Change-Id: I4b7ece238f76d9acb7f0555c180c6336f6cf1830
Implement blueprint: only-update-volume-type-public
Closes-bug: #1493616

commit_message:
Change os-brick to use ostestr

This patch changes the unit tests runs via tox to
use os-testr as the tool to run the tests.  Cinder is
already using ostestr.   This also by default enables
parallel testing.

Change-Id: Iab20bdc2cbd454de2f1d66cea3f68b40b161dc9d

commit_message:
Remove py26 job for openstackclient

py26 will be unsupported in a month or so, remove the job now
since there's no incentive to keep it around.

Change-Id: I5c326848696b6b966c6009fe9cd18bd8dc65bac7

commit_message:
Handle 16-char non-uuid user IDs in payload

If a user_id just happens to be of 16 character length, this will
cause the convert_uuid_bytes_to_hex function to improperly return
a UUID value instead of the user_id string unconverted.

This patch modifies the payload to indicate whether the ID was in
fact a UUID and the attempt to convert to bytes was successful.

This change has effect on more than just user IDs.  It also resolves
potential issues with project IDs, group IDs, IDP IDs, and scope IDs.

Change-Id: Ia4a4f760d67d8bbc22759c48fc800aef016b84ed
Closes-Bug: #1497461
(cherry picked from commit 794e1510cc91fbe0277e291bc2cabdfba478bef3)

commit_message:
Implement aodh venv support

This commit conditionally allows the os_aodh role to
install build and deploy within a venv. This is the new
default behavior of the role however the functionality
can be disabled.

Change-Id: I9f9e09b2a68e843da1d92a782cd29fc563379a6d
Implements: blueprint enable-venv-support-within-the-roles
Signed-off-by: Kevin Carter <kevin.carter@rackspace.com>

commit_message:
Seperated out Telemetry Alarming (Aodh)

The alarming function of Telemetry has been seperated out
by design. This patchset creates new containers for these
alarming services and deploys them accordingly.

See:
http://lists.openstack.org/pipermail/openstack-dev/2015-September/073897.html

DocImpact
UpgradeImpact
Implements: blueprint liberty-release
Change-Id: I25294a25afa76d4d8bddad0a51c48485f33a6d20

commit_message:
Add if condition for random.shuffle

random.shuffle(hosts) only if the length of hosts > 1
then random.shuffle make sense.

Change-Id: I94fbf457a7ca73fe11aa97e52a58cde9298015a7

commit_message:
Add ability to disable warnings being emitted

Provide a helpful fixture that can be used
to disable warnings being output, for testing, or other
purporses.

Closes-Bug: #1503918

Thanks for putting this together. Does it actually show the problem?

I have several concerns with the new coverage:
 - it only handles one branch of configuration (what about warnerrors = False).
 - it only tests with the sphinx installed locally.

Unit tests are great, but I think we need much wider coverage. So - we can add this, but I think we need an integration test (pbr/tests/test_integration) tweak to build the docs, which we then map across *everything* openstack, using each things local dependency versions.

We might even want to go so far as having a test matrix just for docs, running along two dimensions: warnerrors (which btw we really should doc) and sphinx versions.'}, {'account_id': 4162, 'date': '2015-06-23 14:06:04.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

Since we pin to sphinx 1.3 right now, no it didn't show the issue that broke the gate a 2 weeks ago.  That was specific to sphinx 1.2.

For the most part, this was a simple way for me to add code coverage for sphinx.  

I agree that a more detailed matrix will need to be built out, but to be honest this was the first time diving into PBR and unsure how the integration testing works (in the gate).  I'm sure I could figure it out, but it was over the timeline I setup for me to spend on adding the unit test.

Either way, if I can help, I'm more then happy to.  However,  I might need some mentoring or even some collaboration on how this would work."}, {'account_id': 4190, 'date': '2015-09-21 20:59:11.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2: -Code-Review

(6 comments)'}, {'account_id': 6601, 'date': '2015-07-28 15:46:06.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4: Code-Review-1

Should this work in the case of thing2?

    >>> from debtcollector import removals
    >>> import warnings
    >>> warnings.simplefilter("once")
    >>> class OldAndBusted(object):
    ...     @removals.removed_property
    ...     def thing(self):
    ...         return 'old-and-busted'
    ...     @removals.removed_property
    ...     @property
    ...     def thing2(self):
    ...         return 'cat in the hat'
    ...
    >>> o = OldAndBusted()
    >>> o.thing
    __main__:1: DeprecationWarning: Using the 'thing' property is deprecated
    'old-and-busted'
    >>> o.thing2
    __main__:1: DeprecationWarning: None
    Traceback (most recent call last):
      File "<stdin>", line 1, in <module>
      File "debtcollector/removals.py", line 75, in __get__
        return self._fget(instance)
    AttributeError: 'removed_property' object has no attribute '_fget'
    >>>

or am I supposed to replace @property with @removals.removed_property?'}, {'account_id': 1297, 'date': '2015-07-28 23:03:32.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

(4 comments)'}, {'account_id': 1297, 'date': '2015-07-28 23:03:47.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

@James, yup fixing that :)'}, {'account_id': 1297, 'date': '2015-07-28 23:17:02.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 5.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-07-29 03:05:17.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5: Verified+1

@James also ya, no more @property there. This would mean @property would switch to @removed_property; the behavior is the same (except this property descriptor emits messages when used...)'}, {'account_id': 6486, 'date': '2015-07-29 13:24:16.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5:

(2 comments)

Any reason it can't be a decorator on a property? e.g., just

  @removals.removed('Use something instead', version='1.7.0')
  @property
  def prop1(self):
     return 'value'

seems like this would be easier to work with since then you just add a line, and it could be more consistent if "removed" could work with properties as well as functions, etc.'}, {'account_id': 1297, 'date': '2015-07-29 15:27:46.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5:

The only way I know that to work is the following:

  >>> class A(object):
  ...   @property
  ...   @removals.remove(message="gone")
  ...   def c(self):
  ...     return 1
  ... 
  >>> a = A()
  >>> a.c
  __main__:1: DeprecationWarning: Using function/method 'c()' is deprecated: gone
  1

But that doesn't then work in the opposite order:


  >>> class A(object):
  ...   @removals.remove(message="gone")
  ...   @property
  ...   def c(self):
  ...     return 1
  ... 
  >>> a = A()
  >>> a.c
  <BoundFunctionWrapper at 0x7f895a1a5db8 for int at 0x11e0188>

So imho decorating it isn't the right approach, properties (descriptors) are somewhat special in python and afaik can't have decorators easily stacked on them; so thats why this is a new descriptor vs a decorator; would be nice if it was just a decorator but doesn't seem possible...'}, {'account_id': 6486, 'date': '2015-07-29 15:32:03.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 5:

I'm fine with implementing it as a new function now and if we can figure out a different way in future we can switch to that."}, {'account_id': 1297, 'date': '2015-07-29 15:50:53.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 5:

Cool, I'm asking the wrapt author @ https://github.com/GrahamDumpleton/wrapt/issues/44 (he's more aware of all the python peculiarities around this than I am); let's see if he has any thoughts here."}, {'account_id': 1297, 'date': '2015-07-30 04:35:52.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5:

(2 comments)'}, {'account_id': 1297, 'date': '2015-07-30 04:35:54.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 6.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-07-30 17:53:29.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 6: Verified+1

[{'created': '2015-10-15 14:13:57.000000000', 'message': 'Fix usage of "deprecated" markup in docstrings

Replace ".. deprecated:: > 1.5.0" with ".. deprecated:: 1.5.0". Old
HTML output:

    Deprecated since version >: 1.5.0 (...)

The new HTML output:

    Deprecated since version 1.5.0: (...)

Fix also reStructured Text formatting in parse_isotime() docstring.

Change-Id: If8405ff55973056f56f60c4e27e944e7f0e00045
'}]
commit_message:
Fix usage of "deprecated" markup in docstrings

Replace ".. deprecated:: > 1.5.0" with ".. deprecated:: 1.5.0". Old
HTML output:

    Deprecated since version >: 1.5.0 (...)

The new HTML output:

    Deprecated since version 1.5.0: (...)

Fix also reStructured Text formatting in parse_isotime() docstring.

Change-Id: If8405ff55973056f56f60c4e27e944e7f0e00045

John,
99.9% of the time people will likely be putting the cinder private lvm.conf in /etc/cinder.

However there are two points to consider:
1) What if someone is running with the cinder configuration files in a non-standard location, which is permitted/possible for other config file/path related options as things stand; hardcoding /etc/cinder as the container directory for the lvm.conf prohibits them from doing so for a cinder private lvm.conf file.

2) The option is lvm_conf_file; at first glance people would assume that they can use it to point at an lvm.conf located anywhere, not just under /etc/cinder.

Without this change, if I specified lvm_conf_file as /etc/lvm/lvm.conf (a valid file that exists), but an lvm.conf file also exists under /etc/cinder, then Cinder would invoke the 4 query LVM operations pointing at /etc/cinder/lvm.conf, not /etc/lvm/lvm.conf.

As it stands, nothing validates that lvm_conf_file specifies a file called lvm.conf; at best we just validate that the specified file exists...

So perhaps we would be better off with an lvm_conf_dir option in the long run...

Fergal.'}, {'account_id': 2243, 'date': '2015-10-14 15:49:50.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2: Code-Review+2 Workflow+1

@Fergal,
Thanks for the additional thoughts.  I completely agree; it turns out some of the concerns I had were actually my memory failing me in how I set this up.  I was looking at it again this morning and you're right this is certainly a better option I think."}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-10-14 15:49:58.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: -Verified

commit_message:
Use lvm_conf_file directory for LVM_SYSTEM_DIR value.

Currently when LVM_SYSTEM_DIR is added to LVM.LVM_CMD_PREFIX it is
hardcoded as /etc/cinder.

However the configuration option lvm_conf_file could specify a file
located in an arbitrary directory, not just /etc/cinder, so we should
be using the path to the directory containing the specified lvm.conf
file as the value for LVM_SYSTEM_DIR.

Change-Id: I702fdfb3640ef99255fda0fda4d39d0a80ce9dcc
Closes-Bug: #1498651

commit_message:
fix tools/make_test_event_data.py

ceilometer.event.storage.models.Event requires 6 arguments to initialze,
but tools/make_test_event_data.py only provides 5 arguments, so it is
broken now. The missing field is 'raw', which can be safely set to {}.

Change-Id: I4bec3ff66ab9fbec9306be2f1cb0095d148d80fb
Closes-Bug: #1506976

'}, {'created': '2015-09-26 17:29:09.000000000', 'message': '[WIP] Add Monasca Tempest Tests

To run the tests:

1. Create a virtualenv for running the Tempest tests and activate it.
2. Clone the monasca-api, fetch this review, and create a branch.
3. Install the monasca-api which will also register monasca_tempest_tests.
    python setup.py install
4. Clone tempest, and cd to it.
5. Create etc/tempest.conf and etc/logging.conf in the tempest root dir.
6. Run the tests using testr
6.1 Create a list of the monasca tests in a file
    testr list-tests monasca_tempest_tests > monasca_tempest_tests
6.2. Run the tests using testr
    testr run --load-list=monasca_tempest_tests
7. Run the tests using ostestr
        ostestr --regex monasca_tempest_tests

Change-Id: I7d1df1b88b63ccc2f1a66deaf439c032b1175d99
'}, {'created': '2015-09-26 17:41:51.000000000', 'message': '[WIP] Add Monasca Tempest Tests

To run the tests:

1. Clone the OpenStack tempest repo, and cd to it.
2. Create a virtualenv for running the Tempest tests and activate it. For
example in the tempest root dir
    virtualenv .venv
    .venv/bin/activate
2. Install Tempest requirements.
    pip install -r requirements.txt -t test-requirements.txt
    pip install nose
5. Create etc/tempest.conf and etc/logging.conf in the tempest root dir.
2. Clone the monasca-api repo, fetch this review, and create a branch.
3. Install the monasca-api in your venv, which will also register
the Monasca Tempest Plugin as, monasca_tempest_tests. See
http://docs.openstack.org/developer/tempest/plugin.html, for more details.
    python setup.py install
6. Run the tests using testr
6.1 In the Tempest root dir, create a list of the Monasca Tempest Tests
in a file.
    testr list-tests monasca_tempest_tests > monasca_tempest_tests
6.2. Run the tests using testr
    testr run --load-list=monasca_tempest_tests
7. Alternatively, to run the tests using ostestr (no file necessary)
        ostestr --regex monasca_tempest_tests

Change-Id: I7d1df1b88b63ccc2f1a66deaf439c032b1175d99

this cluster and run tests on existing cluster

commit_message:
do not commit requirements syncs

We need to test without committing the requirements changes because pbr
throws an error if the pre and post versioning do not match. The first
change on a stable branch must be the one to remove the pre-versioning
configuration.

Change-Id: I812af614b7a6c7f499c67310f078ac4835b9e91a

commit_message:
test_db_base_plugin_v2: Skip a few tests on some platforms

netaddr (and its underlying libc inet_pton) produces different
representations of IPv4-compat addresses for different platforms.

Linux:
    >>> netaddr.IPAddress("::2")
    IPAddress('::2')
    >>>

OSX:
    >>> netaddr.IPAddress("::2")
    IPAddress('::0.0.0.2')
    >>>

As our API assumes Linux's way, skip affected test cases on
the other platforms.

Related-Bug: #1484837
Change-Id: I89e1822bb92dfcf8772bba1a3edf908c89550119

[{'created': '2015-10-12 17:29:39.000000000', 'message': 'Make websocket run in correct logging mode

Currently websocket always runs in debug mode.
It is because the method variable is passed as a "debug" parameter to
websocket constructor instead of boolean variable.
So websocket will interpret this parameter as true and debug mode will
be on.

This commit makes sure the variable passed as "debug" parameter to
websocket constructor is boolean and really tells if zaqar-server's
debug logging is enabled.
This boolean variable is aquired from the information in local logger
instance.

Change-Id: I701f986a85bdb024c3757ede5a388a78791343aa
Closes-Bug: 1505263
'}]
commit_message:
Make websocket run in correct logging mode

Currently websocket always runs in debug mode.
It is because the method variable is passed as a "debug" parameter to
websocket constructor instead of boolean variable.
So websocket will interpret this parameter as true and debug mode will
be on.

This commit makes sure the variable passed as "debug" parameter to
websocket constructor is boolean and really tells if zaqar-server's
debug logging is enabled.
This boolean variable is aquired from the information in local logger
instance.

Change-Id: I701f986a85bdb024c3757ede5a388a78791343aa
Closes-Bug: 1505263

commit_message:
Fix Simulator Value to 0 that is converted to null

When the value in the simulator is set to zero it is converted to
a null in the publisher. Recently Monasca API has added a check
for the null values and it is rejecting the measurement.
This fixes the issue.

Note: Srinivas already submtted this patch but it does not show
up in github nor can be fetched (public key error)

Change-Id: Ic8e8d73f15c8f3790f7cf127c0bc14dfb816903b

commit_message:
Do not try to delete a veth from a nonexistent namespace

Currently, VethFixture cleanup tries to delete veth from their
namespaces even if they don't exist anymore (without crashing the
cleanup). It implies an extra trace if an error is raised which can be
confusing.

This change avoids to try deleting a veth from a nonexistent namespace
in the fixture VethFixture.

Closes-Bug: #1506862
Change-Id: I5d0192998d2f3f8d1a6f783769ae9bfcb4bae7f2

commit_message:
Do not accept abbreviated CIDRs

This is a special netaddr behavior that we wish to prevent.

http://lists.openstack.org/pipermail/openstack-dev/2015-August/072610.html

APIImpact

Change-Id: I94a059cee396e183bffd4a064709bb83504bf983
Closes-Bug: #1490885

commit_message:
Add correct license for simple modal

Somewhere along the way, the license for simple modal was mishandled.
This patch corrects  it. I am the original author of simple modal.

Change-Id: Ieb4389cfce28f26f85d47aba09da3373d3346f6d
Closes-Bug: #1506565

commit_message:
Prevent the click loss at navbar accordion in integration tests

Simplify code for handling the navbar in integration tests, replace
the loop with explicit waits for the menu items to receive the proper
classes (which mark collapsed/expanded/in-transit states). Besides
fixing intermittent failures this also clarifies the overall logic.

Change-Id: I7a58a59be66264ce6e3c05f78033961954f0c553
Closes-Bug: #1505320

commit_message:
Set cluster status to none when instances in error state

If all the instances in cluster go in ERROR state, the cluster is
still marked BUILDING and the trove task manager is waiting till
cluster_usage_timeout to mark the cluster accordingly.
Now, the cluster goes back to the none state as soon as the
instances are in error state.

Closes-Bug: #1455261

commit_message:
Fix fernet key writing for python 3

When fernet is used to generate a key, it's returned as bytes in
python3 (it's a string in python2).

Writing bytes to a file stream is not allowed if the file is not
binary mode:

   File "/opt/stack/keystone/keystone/token/providers/fernet/utils.py", line 124, in _create_new_key
     f.write(key)
 TypeError: must be str, not bytes

We want the file to contain a string that the admin can look at
rather than bytes so decode bytes to string.

bp python3

Change-Id: I53057a31e3d753bfdae107c0d99bb2fb011741e6

commit_message:
Include d3 and nvd3 as static dependencies.

As the current latest release of nvd3 has a number of major bugs,
we need to use the latest available git release. However, depending
on libraries from `https://` Git repositories is broken on older
versions of npm.

As a workaround, this patch adds nvd3 (and consequently, d3 itself)
as static dependencies using the `vendor-js` mechanism and keeps
the code for each directly within our source tree.

Change-Id: I4fe83ca7eee21dcd1e6d2692f56592e6cb4ea74e

Karma previously started a continuous server to allow for multiple
test runs, which would cause `npm test` to hang when tests finish.
This enables the config option `singleRun` so it quits after tests
have finished running.

can be run properly in a headless environment.

'}]
commit_message:
Use PhantomJS and enforce singleRun for tests.

Karma previously started a continuous server to allow for multiple
test runs, which would cause `npm test` to hang when tests finish.
This enables the config option `singleRun` so it quits after tests
have finished running.

Additionally, this removes Chrome and the Chrome launcher so tests
can be run properly in a headless environment.

commit_message:
Fix incorrect Glance image metadata description

For each image, when user clicks on Edit Image --> Update Metadata, the list
of various available metadata categories and properties is displayed in a
pop-up window. For each category and property, a user-friendly description is
displayed at the bottom of the pop-up.

The description for "Common Operating System Properties" category says - "When
adding an image to Glance, you may specify some common image properties that
may prove useful to consumers of your image." This is too generic and seems
like a copy-paste of the description from glance-common-image-props.json that
the author later failed to update.

Fixing this to show a more meaningful message.

Change-Id: I5477b1702932e07ab1fd499204d3ff1348abba3b
Closes-Bug: #1483063

commit_message:
Upgraded eslint rule libraries.

The newer version of eslint comes with somewhat stricter rules
about indentation and whitespace, so some files have been
adjusted to accomodate.

The newer version of eslint-config-openstack includes a relaxed
version requirement for eslint, as well as a switch/case
indentation update.

The newer version of the angular eslint rules includes a
deprecation rule for $cookieStorage, which has been set to
warning.

Change-Id: Id201a42e3ab484222f938a541507df2e96da2dcf

[{'created': '2015-08-10 01:03:31.000000000', 'message': 'Show the file name when there is an error loading an image metadef file

New image metadata can be added by creating a new json file in the directory
glance/etc/metadefs (this metadata shows up in the image metadata UI on
Horizon dashboard). If the file is loaded successfully, a log message like
the following is printed:

2015-08-09 11:48:34.713 INFO glance.db.sqlalchemy.metadata [-]
File /etc/glance/metadefs/operating-system.json loaded to database.

However, if there is an error loading the file, we get a log message like:

2015-08-09 11:48:34.875 ERROR glance.db.sqlalchemy.metadata [-]
Expecting , delimiter: line 15 column 9 (char 579)

In other words, the file name is not printed. Printing the file name in the
error message will make it easier to debug as we can search the logs using
the file name.

Change-Id: If72fdbb00c58e42aa128ab2b4461a2ae8e55c5aa
Closes-Bug: #1483049
